Cannabis Strains EDA¶

Introduction¶

This dataset was obtained by scraping data from online reviews of different cannabis strains. It contains information on 2170 strains, mostly pertaining to their physiological and psychological effects, as well as their flavour profile. This is an exploratory analysis examining correlations between strain flavours and the medicinal effects, to investigate whether flavour might be a proxy for the underlying chemical profile.

For the scripts used to generate the data and more information on the project, see the corresponding GitHub repository.

As you can see, the majority of the columns are numeric. The values for each of the effects are based on prevalence of those effects in self-reported reviews of customers. For each strain, there are at most 5 effects in 3 parent categories: Effects, Medical, and Negatives.

  • Effects refers to positive side effects, mostly pertaining to the mood it seems to elicit.

  • Medical refers to what medicinal properties the cannabis strain exhibits, also self-reported, and this is perhaps the most interesting class of information in this dataset.

  • Negatives are the negative side effects, such as Dry Mouth, Dry Eyes, Dizzy, Anxious, and Paranoid. These are also interesting because they may contribute negatively to the reviews for a particular strain.

The data is stored in a sparse matrix representation, which unfortunately means that there are a lot of zeroes for each strain. This is because the source of the data only displayed at most 15 effects and 3 flavours, even though the two together make up 80 columns.

Preliminary data visualizations¶

We can do some preliminary visualizations in order to examine various distributions, for instance rating, review count, species, as well as the average values of the different effects and flavours to see how prevalent they are overall. We can then examine these by different flavours, for instance, to see which effects are most prevalent for a particular flavour.

def plot_bar(df, cols, metric='mean'):
    '''Generates a plotly bar graph with the given metric over the given column names.'''
    if metric == 'sum':
        col_vals = df[cols].sum()
    elif metric == 'mean':
        col_vals = df[cols].mean()
        
    data = [dict(
        type ='bar',
        x = cols,
        y = col_vals,
        transforms = [dict(
            type = 'sort',
            target = 'y',
            order = 'descending'
        )]
    )]
    
    iplot(data, validate=False)

def species_barplot(df, x, aggr='mean'):
    grouped = df[x + ['Species']].groupby('Species').agg(aggr).T
    
    trace1 = go.Bar(
        x=x,
        y=grouped['indica'],
        name='indica'
    )
    trace2 = go.Bar(
        x=x,
        y=grouped['sativa'],
        name='sativa'
    )
    trace3 = go.Bar(
        x=x,
        y=grouped['hybrid'],
        name='hybrid'
    )

    data = [trace1, trace2, trace3]
    layout = go.Layout(
        barmode='group'
    )

    fig = go.Figure(data=data, layout=layout)
    iplot(fig)

Hierarchical clustering¶

Clustering features by rank correlation¶

We can use hierarchical clustering combined with the Spearman rank correlation function spearmanr to see if there are natural groupings of flavours and effects according to these metrics. This can give us an idea of both what interesting relationships may exist, and whether our results make sense as a sanity check if we see similar items clustered together.

In [25]:
import scipy
from scipy.cluster import hierarchy as hc

def plot_dendrogram(columns):
    corr = np.round(scipy.stats.spearmanr(df.loc[:, columns]).correlation, 4)
    corr_condensed = hc.distance.squareform(1-corr)
    z = hc.linkage(corr_condensed, method='ward')
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(20,20))
    dendrogram = hc.dendrogram(z, labels=columns, orientation='left', color_threshold=1.2, leaf_font_size=16)
    plt.show()

Seaborn heatmap of correlations¶

Another way to visualize relationships between two sets of variables is to use a heatmap to look at the relative correlations. This way you can look for any bright patches within a particular row or column to see if there are stronger associations between any of the flavours and their corresponding medicinal effects.

In [28]:
import seaborn as sns
corr = df.corr().iloc[2:35, 35:]
fig2 = plt.figure(figsize=(20,20))
sns.heatmap(corr, 
            xticklabels=corr.columns.values,
            yticklabels=corr.index.values)
plt.show()

Examining effects for top flavours¶

We can look at the associated medicinal effects of the three most dominant flavours, Earthy, Citrus, and Sweet, to see which ones appear to be over- or under-represented.

Barplots of earthy, citrus, and sweet flavours vs effects¶

def flavour_barplot(df, x, aggr='mean'):
    earthy = df[x].loc[df['Earthy'] == 1].agg(aggr).T
    citrus = df[x].loc[df['Citrus'] == 1].agg(aggr).T
    sweet = df[x].loc[df['Sweet'] == 1].agg(aggr).T
    
    trace1 = go.Bar(
        x=x,
        y=earthy,
        name='Earthy'
    )
    trace2 = go.Bar(
        x=x,
        y=citrus,
        name='Citrus'
    )
    trace3 = go.Bar(
        x=x,
        y=sweet,
        name='Sweet'
    )

    data = [trace1, trace2, trace3]
    layout = go.Layout(
        barmode='group'
    )

    fig = go.Figure(data=data, layout=layout)
    iplot(fig)

Ranking top flavours for each effect¶

We can also get a count of the number of times each effect appears together with every flavour in order to examine which pairings are most common. Then instead of using absolute numbers, we can rank these associations and try to see which pairings deviate from the norm using a heatmap. First, we'll need to calculate the number of times each effect is non-zero in the same row as each of the individual flavours. Here's an example using just Dry Mouth.

We can generalize this example and create a function that will allow us to create one such column for every one of our medicinal effects, in effect finding the number of times each pairing of effect and flavour appears in our dataset.

In [37]:
def sum_across_cols(df, effects):
    cols = []
    for effect in effects:
        cols.append(df[df[effect] > 0].astype(bool).sum(axis=0)[37:])
    new_df = pd.concat(cols, axis=1)
    new_df.columns = effects
    return new_df

Association rule learning with Apriori¶

Finally, we can use association rule learning to examine which sets of properties appear frequently in our dataset, namely which flavours and effects tend to appear together more often than would be expected given their prevalence in the dataset.
